So-called House of Jason Magnus,/places/312715518,Very large Roman house in the acropolis ridge of Cyrene.
Haut Bécherel,/places/636775194,Haut Bécherel is the site of a major Gallo-Roman sanctuary sacred to Mars.
Borg,/places/272861914,A large Roman courtyard villa covering ca. 7.5 ha.
Skara Brae,/places/80606012,Skara Brae is a stone-built Neolithic settlement located on the west coast of Mainland, the largest island in the Orkney archipelago. Comprised of eight clustered houses, the village was occupied from roughly 3180 to 2500 BC.
Sanctuary of Asklepios at Athens,/places/954340915,A major sanctuary complex located west of the Theatre of Dionysus Eleuthereus on the south slope of the Athenian acropolis.
Roman Agora of Athens,/places/773761100,The Roman agora at Athens is located to the north of the Acropolis and to the east of the ancient Agora.
Crustuminus Ager,/places/485712934,The territory of the city of Crustumerium.
Grimspound,/places/248025633,A prehistoric settlement of the late Bronze Age located in the Dartmoor area of south Devon, England. The remains of 24 stone houses survive within a massive boundary wall.
Quadriporticus of the theatre,/places/568496340,A four-sided portico standing behind the large theater of Pompeii (VIII, 7, 16-17). The complex was constructed ca. 80 BC.
Mystras,/places/410249370,A fortified town in Laconia, Peloponnese, Greece, named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1989.
Rhion,/places/267084998,An ancient harbor and political dependent of Molykreion. Its precise location cannot be determined today.
Maiden Castle, Dorset,/places/232755444,One of the largest and most complex Iron Age hillforts in Europe, Maiden Castle, in Dorset, was occupied from the Neolithic period through to the fourth century AD.
Monte Testaccio,/places/375710890,An artificial mountain on the banks of the Tiber river at Rome composed of 580,000 cubic meters of broken amphorae.
Via Praenestina,/places/622606468,A consular road running from Rome to Praeneste.
Salemi,/places/119040454,Modern town of Salemi, near Trapani, that has been associated with the location of the ancient settlement of Halicyae
Palaiokastro,/places/155598151,Settlement/fortress descibed by Stählin (1924, 224-225); Béquignon (1937, 322-324; Fig. 16).
San Giovanni de Butris,/places/480057748,A church of the eleventh and twelfth century built along the line of the Roman Via Flaminia. The church incorporates Roman remains, including those of a bridge.
Cappuck,/places/104728999,Site of a Roman fort occupied during the Flavian and Antonine periods. It lies 4 miles east of Jedburgh in the Scottish Borders, along the line of Dere Street.
Bridgeness Distance Slab,/places/703547396,Findspot of the Bridgeness distance slab, near the eastern terminus of the Antonine Wall
Varignano Vecchio,/places/362185575,A villa maritima in eastern Liguria, inhabited from ca. 100 BC to the fifth century AD.
So-called Roman Baths in Apollonia,/places/305199887,An architectural complex near the sea in Apollonia. It went through different stages and alterations between, roughly, the fourth century B.C. and the seventh century A.D. It was probably used as a private villa, then as public baths and, perhaps, as cisterns in later years.
So-called Residential Insula in Apollonia,/places/321867660,An architectural complex located on the West side of the East Church in Apollonia (Cyrenaica). Excavated in 1954-55, it was first thought to be a temple of Isis (Stucchi 1975). According to Kenrick (2013), it is more likely to have been a small production centre, maybe for the fermentation of wine.
Settlement near Magrusa,/places/3444300,An ancient settlement near modern site of Magrusa
Vignale,/places/596384814,A Roman villa, mansio and Late Antique settlement along the Via Aemilia Scauri.
Auchinhove camp,/places/26901681,A temporary Roman camp of Flavian date.

Unnamed settlement,/places/889260882,An unnamed settlement on Cercina or Cercinits islands
Nestor's Palace,/places/156116232,A Mycenaean palace complex excavated by the American School of Classical Studies, linked with the Homeric Pylos of Nestor.
Casal Bertone necropolis,/places/505226457,Casal Bertone is named for the modern Roman neighborhood where it was discovered, about 2 km east of the Porta Maggiore.  The site of Casal Bertone covers more than 3,000 square meters.  The eastern portion of the site comprised a residential area that was occupied from about the first century B.C. to the fifth to sixth centuries A.D. 
Cricklade,/places/305841385,Modern day site of a Romano-British settlement in Wiltshire dating from 1st to 4th centuries AD.
Sawtry,/places/427880377,Modern day site of a Roman-British settlement dating from the 2nd to 4th centuries AD.
Curia Iulia,/places/837078212,The building of the Curia Julia was begun by Julius Caesar and completed by Augustus in 29 BCE. It replaced the former senate house, the Curia Hostilia.
Nuraghe S. Cadrina ,/places/359131497,A nuragic village of the Middle Bronze Age (ca. 1700-1350 BC), Nuraghe S. Cadrina has a central tower with an original diameter of 11.70 m.
Blakeia,/places/80227978,A settlement attested in Aristotle's Kymaion Politeia. Its precise location is unknown today but it was located within Cymian territory.
Poggio La Croce,/places/817583144,A fortified Etruscan settlement.
Via Egnatia,/places/196789404,The Via Egnatia was a Roman road begun in the second century BC that crossed the Roman provinces of Illyricum, Macedonia, and Thrace. 
Mundigak,/places/498033127,Mundigak is an archaeological site in Afghanistan's Kandahar province where evidence for a 'palace' belonging to the Harappan transitional phase has been discovered.
Monument near Ghirza,/places/157793747,A monument near the modern site of Ghirza
Fort at Great Wall of Gorgan,/places/9429980,One of the integral forts spaced along the wall
Amphitheatrum Castrense,/places/537585744,The Amphitheatrum Castrense is a Roman amphitheater built in the third century AD. Its structure was later incorporated into the Aurelianic Walls. Adjacent to the amphitheater is the Christian church of Santa Croce in Gerusalemme.
Mausoleum of Galla Placidia,/places/122702818,An ancient funerary chapel, part of the Santa Croce complex in Ravenna, Italy, possibly built as an imperial mausoleum (ca. AD 417 - 425). The empress Galla Placidia (d. AD 450 ) is the presumed, likely patron of the building, though she is very unlikely to have been entombed within one of three sarcophagi found inside.
Arles Roman amphitheater,/places/582640379,The Arles Roman amphitheater was built ca. A.D. 90 and could seat over 20,000 spectators.
tribus Clustumina,/places/943743265,The tribus Clustumina (or Crustumina) was a rural tribe of Rome which was established in 495 B.C. 
House of Marcus Lucretius Fronto,/places/894852237,The House of M. Lucretius Fronto (V, 4, a, 11), situated off the north side of the Via di Nola, is an example of a refined domus that is small in size but with opulent Third and Fourth style wall paintings.
The House of the Masks ,/places/576206943,The House of the Masks (also known as the House of the Comedians), built around 150-100 BC, was a luxurious residential complex that may have housed traveling troops of actors performing at the theater in Delos.
The Theater of Larissa,/places/942647940,The theater at Larissa was a large stone theater built around the end of the third century BC and used for dramatic performances and as a political meeting place.
Telesterion,/places/408217405,The Telesterion (ca. 435 - 421 B.C.) was a sacred hall used for the annual initiation ceremonies for the cult of Demeter and Persephone known as the Eleusinian Mysteries.
Ivor / Xion (river),/places/83424586,The modern Oued Ksob of western Morocco.
Koumasa prepalatial cemetery ,/places/170529772,A prepalatial cemetery on the island of Crete that includes three tholos tombs and one rectangular tomb.
Monte Rocche,/places/659022266,A settlement of the Iron Age and Roman period in western Liguria.
Via Sublacensis,/places/188535571,The Via Sublacensis was built in order to connect the Villa Neronis (Nero's villa at Sublaqueum) to Rome. It split from the Via Valeria near Varia.
Via Herculia,/places/469059303,A Roman road known through epigraphic attestations, the Via Herculia connected Aquilonia and Aequum Tuticum.
Forum Romanum,/places/502866838,The ancient Roman forum.
City Eleusinion at Athens,/places/650003009,The City Eleusinion was one of the most important sanctuaries in the religious life of ancient Athens.  It was the urban “branch” of the sanctuary of Demeter and Kore at Eleusis in use during the Archaic and Classical periods.
Forum of Cosa,/places/6218928,The forum of Cosa functioned as the administrative center of the town and was the site of key administrative and ritual structures.
Vagnari,/places/303135575,A villa, vicus and necropolis site in modern Puglia, Italy located near the modern city of Gravina.  The site was active from the 1st to 4th centuries CE.  
Nuraghe Loelle,/places/171983414,A nuragic site near Caput Tyrsi.
Kh., see Khirbet,/errata/687942,This is not and never should have been a place resource; it was created because a cross-reference that should have been ignored in the Barrington Atlas Map-by-Map Directory was erroneously treated as place data during initial processing. It has therefore been moved from its original location to the errata section and its original URI deprecated.
Kh., see Khirbet,/errata/697680,This is not and never should have been a place resource; it was created because a cross-reference that should have been ignored in the Barrington Atlas Map-by-Map Directory was erroneously treated as place data during initial processing. It has therefore been moved from its original location to the errata section and its original URI deprecated.
Crocifisso del Tufo necropolis,/places/195410768,A major necropolis of Volsinii that reaches its maximum extent between 550 and 450 BC. The necropolis is especially noteworthy on account of its orthogonal layout.
Aqueduct west of Djebel Zid,/places/3156061,An aqueduct connected to areas of centuriation north of Segermes
Temple of Jupiter Optimus Maximus,/places/871801169,The poliadic temple of the city of Rome located on the Capitoline hill.
Abu Simbel,/places/721417202,The site of two temples constructed by Ramesses II, one dedicated to the triad of Amun, Ra-Horakhty, and Ptah, as well as the deified Ramesses, and another dedicated to Hathor and the pharaoh's wife Nefertari. The temple was relocated between 1964 and 1968 to prevent its submersion under Lake Nasser after the construction of the Aswan High Dam.
Spring east of Djebel Zid,/places/535279838,Unlabeled feature captured from the Barrington Atlas

So-called Early Christian Basilica,/places/217728890,A small basilica located outside the walls of the ancient Greek city of Akragas, at the foot of the so-called Temple of Juno, on the eastern slopes of the Hill of the Temples, in an area previously occupied by the necropolis of the late Roman period.
Necropolis of Porta Ercolano,/places/452502505,The Porta Ercolano necropolis, excavated between 1763 and 1838, is the best known of Pompeii's necropoleis, in use from the middle of the first century BC until the first century AD.

Çamlıdere,/places/631385926,Modern name for an otherwise unnamed ancient settlement. It may have been a possession of the Ptolemies, Rhodes, and the Attalid kingdom, and was at least peripherally involved with Rome's war against Aristonikos as a Roman ally.
tribus Pollia,/places/484501230,The tribus Pollia was one of the older rural tribes of Rome.
Minorca (island),/places/572631626,Minorca is one of the Balearic Islands of the Mediterranean Sea. Its name likely derives from the Latin 'Insula minor'.
Arcadian Gate,/places/435916987,The Arcadian Gate is a monumental city gate constructed in the 4th century BCE in Messene.

Monte d'Accoddi,/places/647937672,A ramped, megalithic structure in Sardinia dated to around 2700-2000 BC.
Porta Marina ,/places/615138225,A city gate at the western terminus of the Strada della Marina.
Temple of Venus,/places/663121962,The Temple of Venus (VIII,1) is located adjacent to Pompeii's Porta Marina. The site was cleared in the early year's of the colony to make way for the temple. Seriously damaged by the AD 62 earthquake, the sanctuary was still being rebuilt at the time of its ultimate destruction.
Luceres,/places/749375794,An early Roman tribe from the time of Romulus.
Temple of Victory,/places/37484455,A Greek temple of the Doric order (peripteral hexastyle), built in the fifth century BC, possibly to celebrate a victory against the Carthaginians. Its ruins are still visible in the archaeological site of Himera.
Africa (diocese),/places/154459219,The late Roman diocese of Africa.
Mauretania Caesariensis (late Roman province),/places/991328,A late Roman province within the diocese of Africa.
Tomb of Hilarus Fuscus,/places/242234873,The Late Republican tomb of the freedman Hilarus Fuscus along the Via Appia (ca. 30 B.C.).
tribus Ramnes,/places/531536067,The name of a Roman tribe dating from the earliest period of Roman history.
Via Francigena,/places/136661131,The Via Francigena is a Medieval pilgrimage route connecting Canterbury, England, and Rome.
Hercynian Forest,/places/346732606,An ancient forest located east of the Rhine river in southern Germany. The precise location and extent of the forest remains uncertain, although the Black Forest formed the western part of the Hercynian Forest.
Tuna el-Gebel,/places/54417737,Tuna el-Gebel was the necropolis serving Schmun/Khmun (Hermopolis Magna).

Theatre of Palmyra,/places/514324021,Theatre in the Ancient City of Palmyra. Coordinates determined by eye in Google Earth in November 2012, following description in UNESCO World Heritage List.
Arkadiko Bridge,/places/770053487,An arched Bronze Age bridge near the Mycenaean center of Tiryns. The bridge is located along an ancient highway connecting Tiryns to Epidauros.
Khirbet Beit-Bassa,/places/420569585,An ancient fortress located in Beit Sahour, in the district of Bethlehem in Palestine.
Lapis Niger,/places/326532998,A shrine in the Forum Romanum adjacent to the Republican comitium, recognizable by its distinctive black paving stones. The shrine has been associated, in tradition, with the tomb of Romulus and/or of Faustulus. Giacomo Boni excavated the site between 1899 and 1905.
So-called Area L in Berenike,/places/989143586,The ruins of an ancient building with a large peristyle, probably built around the second century AD, in the southwest area of the archaeological site of Sidi Khiribech, in Berenike (modern Banghazi).
So-called Area H in Berenike,/places/989143587,The ruins of a house of the early Roman period at the archaeological site of Sidi Khiribech, in Berenike. The house had a courtyard with a peristyle. Some of the internal walls were decorated with frescoes representing the Muses.

Hadrumetum/Iustinianopolis,/places/324716,Hadrumetum/Iustinianopolis was an important ancient port in North Africa. Founded by Phoenicians, the site pre-dated Carthage. Under Roman administration the site prospered and Trajan assigned it colonial status as Colonia Concordia Ulpia Trajana Augusta Frugifera Hadrumetina.

Thelepte,/places/324828,Thelepte was a Roman city in Africa Byzacena. It achieved municipal status perhaps in the time of Vespasian and became a colonia under Trajan. The city played an important administrative role in fourth century AD north Africa.

Theveste,/places/324831,Theveste (modern Tébessa, Algeria) became a Roman center and, in the Imperial period, the Legio III Augusta was raised there. In later times Theveste is connected with the Donatists.

Thysdrus,/places/324835,Thysdrus (modern El Djem, Tunisia) was a Punic and Roman city of North Africa. It flourished in the second century AD and built its massive amphitheater in the third century. After an abortive revolt in AD 238, the city was destroyed by soldiers loyal to Maximinus Thrax.

House of Pansa,/places/19985870,The House of Pansa (VI,6,1) is an atrium house in Pompeii that occupies an entire insula. Architectural elements date the structure ca. 140-120 BC in its original phase. The merchant and duumvir Cn. Alleius Nigidius Maius owned the property.
Seleucid Empire,/places/45635759,The Seleucid Empire was a Hellenistic kingdom, founded by Seleucus I Nicator, and ruled by the Seleucid dynasty from 312 to 63 BCE. At its height it stretched from the Aegean Sea to northern India, but it steadily lost territory and prestige. The remnant of the kingdom was eventually incorporated into Roman territory as the province of Syria in 64 BCE.

Attalid kingdom,/places/177302800,Founded by Philetaerus, who took command of Pergamum in 282 BCE, and declared independent by Attalus I in the 230's BCE, the Attalid kingdom was allied closely to Rome; the kingdom expanded after the Peace of Apamea in 188 BCE. The last king, Attalus III, willed the kingdom to Rome, and after his death in 133, the former kingdom formed the core of the Roman province of Asia.

Aleksandrovo tumulus,/places/845876618,The Aleksandrovo tumulus or kurgan is a Thracian burial mound located near Aleksandrovo in south-eastern Bulgaria, that dates to the fourth century BC.
Reccopolis,/places/668575405,Reccopolis is an urban, Visigothic, ex-novo foundation made under king Liuvigild in A.D. 578. The archaeological remains at the site include a palace complex, public area, basilica, walls, and aqueduct. The site is known today by the Spanish version of its Latin name (Recópolis); it is located near the modern village of Zorita de los Canes in the Spanish province of Guadelajara.

Roman amphitheater at Santa Maria Capua Vetere,/places/93820013,Sometimes referred to as the "Anfiteatro Campano", the Roman amphitheater at Santa Maria Capua Vetere is the second largest in the Roman world. Begun under Augustus, it was further renovated under Hadrian and Antoninus Pius.

House of the Tragic Poet,/places/912505596,The so-called "House of the Tragic Poet" (VI, 8, 3, 5) was built in the first century BC and has the plan of a classic "Samnite" house. The house was excavated in 1824. It lies at the corner of the Via delle Terme and the Via della Fullonica, across from the Forum Baths.
tribus Poblilia,/places/964333742,Tribus Poblilia was a later rural tribe of Rome, which was established in 358 B.C.

Qal’at Salah El-Din/Fortress of Saladin,/places/397378357,An ancient castle, located in modern Syria. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2006 as part of the "Crac des Chevaliers and Qal’at Salah El-Din" listing.
S. Costanza,/places/528606605,A fourth century AD structure along the Via Nomentana that was built by Constantine I as a mausoleum, originally housing the remains of his daughters Constantina and Helena. It was dedicated as a Christian church in the Middle Ages.
Achladia,/places/598926917,A Minoan site in eastern Crete that was the site of a so-called "large rural villa" covering some 270 square meters and dating to the Middle Minoan and Late Minoan periods.
Necropoli di San Placido,/places/888447551,A large Roman necropolis in Messina, uncovered in 1914 during the works to build the modern Palazzo della Prefettura.
Circus Maximus,/places/458808506,An ancient chariot-racing venue at Rome and a major location for public entertainments (ludi), the Circus Maximus is located between the Aventine and Palatine hills.
Glanum dam,/places/819897603,A Roman dam that created the Lac du Peirou and supplied Glanum with water. While the ancient dam was destroyed in the late nineteenth century, the reservoir remains.
Pen-y-Gaer Roman fort,/places/776990479,A Roman auxiliary fort in Powys, situated midway along the Roman road linking the forts at Brecon Gaer (Cicutio) and Abergavenny (Gobannio).
tribus Palatina,/places/741137357,An urban tribe of Rome created under the reign of Servius Tullius.
Red Basilica,/places/923431995,A Roman temple built above the Selinus river which was originally constructed for the worship of Egyptian gods, most likely Isis and/or Serapis.  In the Byzantine era it was converted into a church of St. John. It was subsequently ruined, although the rotunda on the north side is still an active mosque. 
Honorific arch,/places/795615129,An honorific arch built in Pompeii near the intersection of the streets known by the modern names of the Via della Fortuna and the Via di Mercurio.
House of Obellius Firmus,/places/182931390,The House of M. Obellius Firmus lies south of the Via di Nola and is also known as the House of the Count of Turin. Excavated in 1910, the house's name is derived from electoral graffiti found on the site. (IX, 14, 2, 4, a, b)

House of Publius Casca Longus,/places/836029917,The House of Publius Casca Longus (I, 6, 11) is located on the Via dell'Abbondanza and is also known as the Casa dei Quadretti Teatrali.
Rouweyha,/places/674925422,An ancient place, located in modern Syria, with remains of an ancient basilica, residential buildings, and several tombs. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011 as part of the "Ancient Villages of Northern Syria."

Olympos (mountain),/places/208278117,A mountain located on the northeast tip of the island of Cyprus and mentioned by Strabo. One of several mountains scattered throughout the Greek world known by this name.  Not to be confused with the main peak of the Trogodos mountains, which is today called "Mount Olympus" and lies in the center of the island.

Uruk/Orchoe/Erech/Orikut,/places/912986,Uruk was an ancient Sumerian (and later Babylonian) city located on the Euphrates river. At its height (ca. 2900 BC), Uruk's population may have topped 50,000 people and its walls enclosed an area of more than six square kilometers, making it the largest city in the world at that point in time.

Antonine Wall,/places/91357,A series of fortifications approximately 63 km in length, spanning the breadth of modern day Scotland between the Firth of Forth and the Firth of Clyde. The Antonine Wall was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2008.
Hadrian's Wall,/places/91358,Hadrian's Wall or Vallum Aelium was the first of two Roman fortifications built across northern Britannia. The project was begun in A.D. 122 and the works eventually stretched from the River Tyne near the North Sea to the Solway Firth on the Irish Sea. The wall represented the northern limit of the Roman Empire.

Graupius M.,/places/92147,Site of Roman military victory over the native Caledonians in AD 83 or 84, chronicled in Tacitus' Agricola. Its location has never been conclusively identified, notwithstanding centuries of scholarly debate. Dozens of candidate sites have been proposed (and dismissed) over the years, however, the general consensus seems to agree upon a location somewhere in northeast Scotland extending north from Perthshire well into Aberdeenshire.

Ardashir-Khurra/Gur/[Firuzabad],/places/922617,Ardashir-Khurra/Gur/[Firuzabad] was an ancient Persian city. Alexander of Macedonia destroyed the original settlement of Gōr, which was later revived by Ardashir I, founder of the Sassanid dynasty.

Pasargadae/Batrakatash,/places/922693,Pasargadae/Batrakatash was an ancient Persian city and the capital of Cyrus the Great (559–530 BC). It remained the capital until Cambyses II moved it to Susa. The site is listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
Persepolis/Parsa/Persai/Sat Setun,/places/922695,Persepolis/Parsa/Persai/Sat Setun was the ceremonial capital of the Achaemenid Empire. The origins of the settlement belong to the sixth century BC (ca. 515). The archaeological site was named as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1979.

Lugdunum,/places/99003,Lugdunum Batavorum, also referred to as  Brittenburg, is the site of Roman ruins near Katwijk aan Zee that emerged in the sixteenth century at the mouth of the Oude Rijn (old river Rhine). The site is connected with the Roman frontier system (limes) of Germania Inferior.

Burdigala,/places/138248,Burdigala (modern Bordeaux) was a Celtic center of the Bituriges Vivisci. The Romans lost a battle at the site in 107 BC, with consul Lucius Cassius Longinus being killed in the action. Rome eventually controlled the area ca. 60 BC.

Stoa of Attalos,/places/759679649,The Stoa of Attalos, located on the eastern side of the ancient Athenian agora, is a long, rectangular, two-story building of limestone and marble, with an external and internal colonnade. It was originally constructed around 150 BCE and then reconstructed in the 1950s.

Caimeni,/places/905386158,Caimeni is a name ascribed to the geological predecessors of Palea and Nea Kameni. The two later islands were formed by volcanic activity between AD 1620 and 1850.

Caepionis Monu.,/places/256038,Caepionis Monumentum (Tower of Caepio) was a tower-cum-lighthouse built by the Roman proconsul Quintus Servilius Caepio in 140 BC. The aim was to make the Salmedina reef at the mouth of the river Baitis (Guadalquivir) navigable. The modern toponym is Chipiona.

Via Cassia,/places/447759107,An ancient Roman road branching off from the Via Flaminia and continuing to Luna where it joined the Via Aurelia.
Via Clodia,/places/737328394,An ancient Roman road.
Arch of Gallienus,/places/29110684,The Arch of Gallienus marked the Porta Esquilina, a gate in the Servian Wall of Rome. The via Labicana and via Tiburtina issue from Rome at this point. The Arch was erected in AD 262.
Thermae Antoninianae,/places/322942899,The Thermae Antoninianae, commonly known as the Baths of Caracalla, were built in Rome between AD 212 and 216.
Beni Hasan,/places/112509596,A Middle Kingdom cemetery known for its rock-cut tombs of local officials.    
Amarna,/places/149576487,A new capital for Egypt founded by Akhenaten during his reign as pharaoh during Egypt's Eighteenth Dynasty. 
Cavalon River,/places/54430875,Tributary of the Druentia fl. (Durance)
Corinth Canal,/places/131418574,The Corinth Canal cuts across the Isthmus of Corinth, connecting the Gulf of Corinth to the Saronic Gulf and the Aegean Sea. Several abortive attempts in antiquity were made at creating the canal, although its final (and functional) realization occurred in modernity.
Prestatyn,/places/718938476,Modern day site of a Romano-British settlement dating from 1st to 2nd centuries AD.
Old Oswestry,/places/198909520,Old Oswestry is an Iron Age hill fort located  in northwest Shropshire, England.
Kato Phournos Tomb,/places/661894078,The Kato Phournos Tomb is one of the nine tholos, or "beehive", tombs found around the acropolis of Mycenae. It is thought to have been constructed between 1460 and 1400 BC.
Library of Pergamum,/places/117689032,The Library of Pergamum was constructed by the Attalid ruler Eumenes ll on the acropolis of the city of Pergamon between 197 and 159 BCE to house a vast collection of literary and philosophical works. 
Temple of Aphrodite Euploia,/places/312238265,The temple of Aphrodite Euploia is a tholos constructed in the fourth century BC in Knidos, a coastal city on the Datça Peninsula. It was built to house Praxiteles' famous nude statue of Aphrodite.
San Crisogono,/places/883684762,San Crisogono (sacred to San Crisogono) is one of the early parish churches (tituli) of Rome. Pope Silvester I (314–335) likely builds the first iteration in the fourth century AD; later reworkings occur in the twelfth and seventeenth centuries, respectively.
Chauvet Cave,/places/165753155,The Chauvet-Pont-d'Arc Cave in southern France contains the earliest known and best preserved figurative cave paintings in the world, dating from the Upper Paleolithic. The cave was discovered on December 18, 1994, and was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List on June 22, 2014.
Māri,/places/286681704,An ancient Semitic city that flourished as a trade center and hegemonic state between 2900 BC until 1759 BC. A place from the TAVO Index.
Acropolis of Athens,/places/638356144,The acropolis of the ancient city of Athens in Greece.
Hephaisteion,/places/558659669,The temple of Hephaistos located on the northwest side of the Agora of Athens.
Tigurini,/places/522967769,A sub-tribe of the Helvetii.
Palatinus Mons,/places/971691208,The central hill of Rome, Italy. Legend held that Romulus founded the city of Rome on the Palatine.
Aventinus mons,/places/865014139,One of the seven hills of Rome. Until the reign of the emperor Claudius, the hill lay outside the pomerium of the city.
Myrtonion,/places/528109753,A fortress in Thrace, whose precise location is now unknown.
Pons Cestius,/places/211668069,A Roman stone bridge on the Tiber river, spanning the river channel from the Tiber Island westward to the Transtiberim (Trastevere). The original bridge dates to the first century BC.
Temple of Hera II (Neptune),/places/42219804,A fifth century B.C. Doric temple, the so-called Temple of Hera II is also sometimes referred to as the Temple of Neptune.
Roman theater at Benevento,/places/12766857,A Roman theater of the second century A.D. constructed during the reign of Hadrian.
Copper and Gold Mine at Kantanos,/places/409810773,Southeast of the ancient settlement of Kantanos on Crete (BAtlas 60 A2)

Damietta Branch,/places/434655354,A place from the TAVO Index
al-Ḥilla,/places/434655355,A place from the TAVO Index
Via Augusta,/places/803793619,A Roman road stretching some 1,500 km from Cádiz to the Coll de Panissars.
Via Appia,/places/356966898,An early Roman road (via publica) originating at Rome and terminating at Brundisium, the Via Appia was begun in the fourth century BC by the censor Appius Claudius Caecus. The Latin author Statius described the Via Appia as "queen of the long roads".
Via Labicana,/places/74935822,An ancient Roman road connecting Rome and Labicum.
Mehring,/places/782507577,Roman villa rustica in Mehring
Combe Down,/places/544572531,Site of a Romano-British villa of courtyard type.
Sarresdorf,/places/597847356,Roman villa rustica
Oylum,/places/275382665,Oylum Höyük is a settlement mound that was inhabited from the fourth millennium BC until the Hellenistic period.
Moenjodaro,/places/902113570,An ancient (third millennium BC) city of the Indian sub-continent connected with the Harappan Civilization. It  was designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1980.
Hiera Oikia, Eleusis,/places/935032928,The so-called "Hiera Oikia" at Eleusis was a religious sanctuary that dates ca. 700 - 600 B.C.
Temple of Athena Pronaia,/places/513711610,The Temple of Athena Pronaia, located at Delphi, is a peripteral Doric building (6 x 12 columns). It was built ca. 500 BC and is the largest building in the sanctuary of Athena Pronaia.
Amnisos,/places/524143100,A Bronze Age site on the north shore of Crete that may have served as a port for Knossos.
Ba’uda,/places/488293484,Ruins of an ancient city, located in modern Syria. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011 as part of the "Ancient Villages of Northern Syria."
Qalb Lozé,/places/587486978,An ancient place, located in modern Syria, with remains of an ancient basilica. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011 as part of the "Ancient Villages of Northern Syria."
Deirouné,/places/587486979,An ancient place, located in modern Syria, with remains of a monastic chapel. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011 as part of the "Ancient Villages of Northern Syria."
Kafr Aqareb,/places/587486980,An ancient place, located in modern Syria, with remains of Roman praetorium, a temple and grottoes for pagan worship, a Byzantine basilica, and a large communal reservoir. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011 as part of the "Ancient Villages of Northern Syria."
Crac des Chevaliers,/places/587486981,An ancient castle, located in modern Syria. Inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2006 as part of the "Crac des Chevaliers and Qal’at Salah El-Din" listing.
Villa of Horace,/places/431558511,The archaeological remains of a villa near Licenza, Italy, that are traditionally connected with the Latin poet Horace.
Tiran Island,/places/594456491,Tiran (Arabic: جزيرة تيران‎ Jazīrat Tīrān) is an island located in the Straits of Tiran, which separate the Red Sea from the Gulf of Aqaba.
Sanafir Island,/places/290587550,An island in the Red Sea to the east of Tiran island.
Gallo-Roman sites at Érome, France,/places/747563988,A pair of archaeological sites in Gallia Narbonensis. The site of Les Orpaillots shows traces of a sanctuary and a group of tombs while Notre-Dame-de-la-Mure showed traces of a late third century Gallo-Roman villa.
Comblessac,/places/44707452,A heptagonal Gallo-Roman temple.
H., see Horvat,/errata/687912,This is not and never should have been a place resource; it was created because a cross-reference that should have been ignored in the Barrington Atlas Map-by-Map Directory was erroneously treated as place data during initial processing. It has therefore been moved from its original location to the errata section and its original URI deprecated.

Napoca,/places/207304,Napoca (modern Cluj-Napoca) was an ancient Roman settlement established after the conquest of Dacia in AD 106. It became a provincial capital of Dacia Porolissensis and was abandoned in the late third century. Its name appears on the Roman milestone found in nearby Aiton.

Qubbet el-Hawa,/places/979588215,Qubbet el-Hawa is a site of a group of rock cut tombs known as the Princes' Tomb on the west side of the Nile, opposite Aswan. The tombs mostly date to the Old Kingdom.

House of the Ship Europa,/places/104925762,The so-called "House of the Ship Europa" is a large house in the Roman city of Pompeii  (I,15,3) that takes its conventional, archaeological name from a large graffito of ship bearing the legend 'Europa'.

West Coker,/places/70083736,Site of 3rd/4th century Roman villa. Also the findspot of a bronze statuette of Mars and an bronze ansate plate inscribed with a dedication to Mar Rigisamus (RIB 187).
Santa Sabina,/places/715215852,A Christian basilica on the Aventine hill in Rome founded in the fourth century AD. The church takes its name from a Christian martyr who was said to have lived on the Aventine. The church is the oldest extant Roman basilica structure that preserves its original plan in the city of Rome.
Medinet Habu,/places/321318358,The New Kingdom mortuary temple of Ramesses III at Medinet Habu, on the West bank of the Nile near Luxor.
Holy Valley,/places/657612457,The Qadisha valley is one of the most important early Christian monastic settlements in the world. It was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1998.
Kaneš,/places/58129442,Kaneš or Kanesh (Hittite: Neša) is located adjacent to modern Kültepe, thus at times the site is referred to as Kültepe Kaneš. The site was one of continuous occupation from the Chalcolithic period to the time of the Roman empire, although its cultural zenith was as a major Hittite site that was the site of a large merchant quarter (kârum) of the Old Assyrian kingdom (ca. twentieth to sixteenth centuries BC).
Stanegate,/places/506349985,An important Roman military road built in what is now northern England, linking the Corbridge in the east and Carlisle in the west. A later western addition may have linked the fort at Kirkbride.
Ġgantija,/places/62131047,Megalithic temple on the island of Gozo; named a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1980

Nea Moni,/places/514403427,An eleventh century monastery on  Chios built by Constantine IX Monomachos. The site was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1990.

Ermine Street,/places/203193875,The Ermine Street was a major Roman road of Britain, running from Londinium to Colonia Lindum and Eburacum.
Via Caecilia,/places/512741502,The Via Caecilia left the Via Salaria at the 35th mile and continued to the Adriatic coast.
Vigna Randanini,/places/874652177,A Jewish catacomb along the Via Appia discovered in 1859.
Auditorium Maecenatis,/places/866548110,An early Imperial building on the Esquiline Hill in Rome, the Auditorium Maecenatis has been connected with Maecenas as it stands in the area of his gardens (horti). While its precise function is unknown, the building may have served as a conservatory.
Thermae Agrippae,/places/22073979,The Thermae Agrippae, built by M. Vipsanius Agrippa in the Campus Martius, were the earliest of Rome's great public baths.
tribus Galeria,/places/986788581,The tribus Galeria was one of the older rural tribes of ancient Rome
Forum Boarium,/places/305567842,The so-called "Forum Boarium" in Pompeii was erroneously named by its 1755 excavators who discovered the bones of large bovids and assigned the name that still is used to describe this insula in Pompeii's Regio II (II, 5).
Temple of Apollo,/places/780913480,The Temple of Apollo (VII,7,32) in Pompeii is one of the city's oldest cults, dating to the sixth century BC. The sanctuary assumed its present appearance in the second century BC.
Apollo, Aedes,/places/740034026,The likely site of the original sanctuary to Apollo at Rome. The visible remains belong to the Augustan phase.
San Teodoro al Palatino,/places/76960231,A church on the Palatine Hill in Rome sacred to Saint Theodore of Amasea dating originally to the sixth century AD.
Arcus Dolabellae et Silani,/places/159953179,Situated on the Caelian Hill, the Arcus Dolabellae et Silani sits at the northern corner of the Castra Peregrina.
Sant'Agata di Militello,/places/880325202,A modern town in Sicily that has been associated with the location of the ancient settlement of Agathyrnum.
Hafir far west of Araba,/places/599490806,A waterhole essential to the ancient Sudanese pastoral economy
Podere Cosciano,/places/879707568,Etrusco-Roman farm site
Kallipatrai,/places/21349240,A chorion (probably a small village, farm or estate), attested only in a single inscription, and probably located somewhere south of the site of Larisa in Aiolis.
House of the Moralist,/places/557684935,The so-called House of the Moralist, also known as the House of M. Epidius Hymenaeus, is located on the Via dell'Abbondanza. The house was formed from two connecting properties that belonged to two related wine-merchants, T. Arrius Polites and M. Epidius Hymenaeus ( III, 4, 2-3).
Castronuovo di Sicilia,/places/816414429,A modern location in Sicily that has been associated with the location of the ancient settlement of Krastos.

Ager Gallicus,/places/413004,A region of Italy in which Gallic settlement had taken place after 400 BC. This territory was captured by Rome following the battle of Sentinum in 295 BC.
Alba Fucens,/places/413005,A town of the Aequi along the Marsic frontier where the Romans established a Latin colony in 304/3 BC. Alba Fucens was a significant center of the middle republican period and became a place where Rome kept state prisoners, including Syphax of Numidia, Perseus of Macedonia, and Bituitus, king of the Arverni.
Albinia (river),/places/413006,The Albegna is a river of southern Tuscany and flows from Monte Amiata to the Tyrrhenian Sea.

Ameria,/places/413012,Ameria, claimed by Cato the Elder as the oldest town in Umbria, was an important center that may have gained Roman municipal status as early as 338 BC, following the Latin War.
Amiternum,/places/413013,Amiternum was an ancient settlement of the Sabines that Rome captured in 293 BC. The settlement was situated at the intersection of four Roman roads: the Via Caecilia, the Via Claudia Nova, and the two branches of the Via Salaria. The historian Sallust was born at Amiternum in 86 BC.
Ancon(a),/places/413014,A port city founded by colonists from Syracuse in 387 BC.
Anguillara,/places/413015,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Anguillara
Anneianum,/places/413016,Anneianum was located in the Etruscan Apennines, along the road from Faventia to Florentia.
Anxanum,/places/413017,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 G4 Anxanum
*Aprutium,/places/413019,An ancient region of eastern Italy (modern Abruzzo).
Aqua Viva,/places/413021,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Aqua Viva
Aquae Apollinares,/places/413022,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Aquae Apollinares
Aquae Apollinares Novae,/places/413023,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Aquae Apollinares Novae
Aquae Cutiliae,/places/413024,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Aquae Cutiliae
Aquae Passeris,/places/413025,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Aquae Passeris
Aquae Tauri,/places/413026,A thermal site in Etruria northeast of Centumcellae.

Armenta fl.,/places/413029,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 Armenta fl.
Arna,/places/413030,Arna was an ancient city of Umbria.
Arretium,/places/413032,Arretium (the Etruscan Aritim) was one of the duodecim populi Etruriae and described by Livy as one of the "Capitae Etruriae".  The Romans captured the city in 311 B.C. and it became a station on the via Cassia.
Asciano,/places/413035,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Asciano
Asculum,/places/413036,Asculum (modern Ascoli Piceno) was the principal city of the Piceni.
Asisium,/places/413037,A Roman settlement built over an Umbrian one on a western foothill of the Appenines. It received municipal status and was assigned to the  Tribus Sergia. Totila destroyed most of the city in A.D. 545.
Aspia (river),/places/413038,The Aspio river.
Aternum,/places/413039,Aternum (modern Pescara) was a settlement at the mouth of the Aternus river.
Aternus (river),/places/413040,The Aterno-Pescara river.
Attidium,/places/413041,An ancient settlement of Umbria mentioned only by Pliny the Elder. Numerous inscriptions discovered at the site indicate that Attidium achieved the status of a municipium.
*Aufenginum,/places/413042,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 *Aufenginum
Aufinum,/places/413043,Aufinum (modern Ofena) was an ancient center of the Abruzzo. Pliny lists the Aufinates Cismontani among the communities of the Vestini.
*Aurinia/Saturnia,/places/413044,An Etruscan town that Dionysius of Halicarnassus claimed had been founded by the Pelasgians, Saturnia received a Roman colony in 183 BC.
Auximum,/places/413045,Auximum (modern Osimo) is an ancient settlement of Picenum. The original foundation was likely carried out by Greeks from Ancona. The Romans made it a base for military operations from 174 BC.
Aveia,/places/413046,Aveia was a settlement of the Vestini in the valley of the Aterno river.
Avens (river),/places/413047,A river of the Sabine territory.
Axia,/places/413048,Axia was an Etruscan center located to the west of Viterbo.
Baccanae,/places/413050,Baccanae was a road station along the Via Cassia.
Badies,/places/413051,Badies is a site (vicus) along the Via Salaria mentioned in the Antonine Itinerary. Its location is no longer certain.
Balneum Regis,/places/413052,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C3 Balneum Regis
Batinus? (river),/places/413053,The Batinus? is mentioned by Pliny and may correspond to the Tordino river.
Blera,/places/413054,An Etruscan town located on the Via Clodia.
Caelanum,/places/413056,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Caelanum
Cales,/places/413058,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Cales
Caletranus Ager,/places/413059,The Caletranus Ager was the territory surrounding the Etruscan city of Caletra.
Camerinum,/places/413060,Camerinum was a town in Umbria on the frontiers of Picenum that was allied to Rome from 309 B.C.
Campovalano,/places/413061,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Campovalano
Capena,/places/413062,An ancient urban center in Faliscan territory adjacent to Etruria, Capena was sacked by the Romans in 390 BC. 
Capestrano,/places/413063,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Capestrano
Carsulae,/places/413065,An ancient settlement originating the late fourth or third centuries BC and lying along the route of the Roman Via Flaminia.
Casone,/places/413066,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A2 Casone
Castellina,/places/413067,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A2 Castellina
Castelluccio di Pienza,/places/413068,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Castelluccio di Pienza
Castellum Firmanorum,/places/413069,Castellum Firmanorum was the ancient port of Firmum Picenum.
Castelsecco,/places/413070,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Castelsecco

Casuentillani,/places/413075,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 Casuentillani
Centum Cellae,/places/413076,Centum Cellae (modern Civitavecchia) was an ancient coastal settlement in Tyrrhenian Etruria. The emperor Trajan re-builds the harbor at the site and Pliny the Younger mentions its name, Centum Cellae.
Cetamura,/places/413077,Cetamura is an ancient hilltop settlement with occupation phases stretching from the Etruscans to the Romans to the Medieval period. The site is located near Gaiole, Radda and Castellina in Chianti, Italy.
Chianciano Terme,/places/413078,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Chianciano Terme
Le Ciliegeta,/places/413079,The site of Le Ciliegeta, near the source of the river Arno, served as a rich stips votiva. The site was discovered in 1836. The finds included over 600 bronzes, more than 1,000 pieces of aes rude, 2000 weapons and other artifacts.
Ciminius L.,/places/413080,A caldera lake of northern Latium.
Ciminius M.,/places/413081,A volcanic massif rising 1053 meters above sea level; the modern Monte Cimino.
Cingulum,/places/413082,Cingulum was a town in Picenum. 
*Cingulus M.,/places/413083,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 *Cingulus M.
Civita,/places/413084,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C3 Civita

La Cività di Spedino,/places/413086,La Cività di Spedino was a fortified upland center (951 m ASL) in the territory of the Aequi.
Civitalba,/places/413087,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D2 Civitalba
Clanis (river),/places/413088,Clanis fl. (Chiana river) is a river of central Italy that flows into the Tiber river.
Clasius? (river),/places/413089,Clasius? fl., a river of Umbria and part of the Tiber river's basin.
Cliternia,/places/413090,An ancient city of northern Apulia located near Larinum.
Clitumnus (river),/places/413091,A small river of Umbria.
Clocoris fl.,/places/413092,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 G4 Clocoris fl.
Cluana,/places/413093,Cluana was an ancient settlement in Picenum.
*Cluentus (river),/places/413094,The Chienti river.
Clusinus L.,/places/413095,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Clusinus L.
Clusium,/places/413096,Clusium, the Etruscan Clevsin (modern Chiusi), was a major city of Etruria. Lars Porsena was a sixth century BC king of Clusium.
Cluviae,/places/413097,A city of the Carricini Samnites.
Colle delle Fate,/places/413098,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Colle delle Fate
Colle Plinio,/places/413099,A hilltop villa near Tifernum Tiberinum commonly associated with one of the villas of Pliny the Younger.
Collepezzuto,/places/413100,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Collepezzuto
Contrada Altavilla,/places/413101,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Contrada Altavilla

Corchiano,/places/413103,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Corchiano
Corciano,/places/413104,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C2 Corciano
Corfinium,/places/413105,Corfinium was the principal city of the Paeligni in the valley of the Aternus river. The site becomes the capital of the breakaway Italic groups that oppose Rome during the Social War.
Cortona,/places/413106,An Umbrian city that, under Etruscan influence, expanded and came to be called 'Curtun'. Later it became the Roman colony Cortino.
Cosa,/places/413107,A Latin colony in south Etruria founded ca. 273 B.C.
Crustumius (river),/places/413108,Crustumius fl. (Conca river)
La Cuma,/places/413109,The principal archaeological remains found in the "La Cuma" site are those of a late Republican sanctuary dating to the second and first centruies B.C. 
Cumara? (river),/places/413110,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Cumara? fl.
Cunerum Pr.,/places/413111,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F1 Cunerum Pr.
Cupra Maritima,/places/413112,Cupra Maritima was a coastal city of Picenum (regio V) assigned to the tribus Velina.
Cupra Montana,/places/413113,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Cupra Montana
Cures,/places/413114,Cures (also Cures Sabini) was a Sabine city located in the Tiber river valley along the Via Salaria. The Romans conquered Cures in 290 BC under M'. Curius Dentatus and granted it status as a municipium in the tribus Sergia.
Cutiliensis L.,/places/413115,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Cutiliensis L.
Doganella,/places/413118,Doganella was an important Etruscan settlement of the Albegna valley, occupied between ca. 600 and 400 B.C. The city may have comprised as many as 240 ha.
Eretum,/places/413121,Eretum was a settlement of the Sabines and is involved in legendary accounts of early Rome.
Etruria/Tuscia,/places/413122,Etruria/Tuscia was an ancient region of Central Italy inhabited by the Etruscans.
Faesulae,/places/413124,Faesulae (modern Fiesole) was an Etruscan foundation called Viesul, Viśl, or Vipsul. The city was conquered by Romans in 283 B.C. Sulla would settle Roman veterans there. Citizens of the town supported the conspiracy of Catiline.
Falerii,/places/413125,A fortified town located some 6 km from Falerii Veteres and established by the ancient Romans ca. 241 BC. (cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Falerii)
Falerii Veteres,/places/413126,A Faliscan settlement (cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Falerii Veteres)
Falerio,/places/413127,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Falerio
Falisci,/places/413128,The name for a group of Italic people who occupied the Ager Faliscus within Etruria.
Fanum Fortunae,/places/413129,Fanum Fortunae, the site of a shrine to Fortuna, is first mentioned in the ancient sources in 49 B.C. when Iulius Caesar held the town. An Augustan colony was established at the site and the Romans prevailed in the Battle of Fano in A.D. 271. The town was eventually destroyed by the Ostrogoths.
Fanum Fugitivi,/places/413130,A road station on the Via Flaminia, located between Interamna and Spoletium.
Farfarus fl.,/places/413131,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Farfarus fl.
Ferentium,/places/413132,Ferentium (modern Ferento) was a city of Etruria first mentioned in the Liber Coloniarum ca. 123 BC that became a Roman municipium after the Social War. Substantial remains of the city remain; the site was the birthplace of Otho and noted for its fine stone monuments and statues.
Fescennium,/places/413133,Fescennium (modern Narce) was a Faliscan settlement located ca. 5 km south of Falerii Veteres. 
*Firmidianum,/places/413134,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 *Firmidianum
Firmum Picenum,/places/413135,Firmum Picenum was founded as a Latin colony in 264 BC with 6,000 colonists. It received municipal status after 48 BC.
Fisternae,/places/413136,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Fisternae
Flaminia,/places/413137,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Flaminia
Florentia,/places/413138,Florentia (modern Florence / Firenze) was founded as a colony for military veterans ca. 80 B.C. by Lucius Cornelius Sulla.
Flusor (river),/places/413139,The Potenza river.
Fons Clitumni,/places/413140,Originally the site of a shrine dedicated to the river god Clitumnus and later a paleochristian shrine. The temple was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011.
Fontecchio,/places/413141,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Fontecchio
Foruli,/places/413142,Foruli was a Sabine town located between Amiternum and Interocrea.
Forum Aurelii,/places/413143,A settlement in Etruria situated on the Via Aurelia placed by between Centumcellae and Cosa by the Antonine Itinerary.
Forum Cassii,/places/413144,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Forum Cassii

Forum Flaminii,/places/413147,A town founded in 220 B.C. by Caius Flaminius during the construction of the Via Flaminia. 
Forum Novum,/places/413148,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Forum Novum
Forum Sempronii,/places/413149,An ancient Roman colony, founded in the time of Gaius Sempronius Gracchus.

Galeata,/places/413154,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 Galeata
Ghiaccio Forte,/places/413156,Ghiaccio Forte was an Etruscan settlement, most likely founded in the fourth century BC, that was sacked by the Romans ca. 280 BC.
Graviscae,/places/413157,The port of the Etruscan city of Tarquinia.
Grotte di Castro,/places/413158,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Grotte di Castro

Grotte di Torri,/places/413160,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Grotte di Torri
Hatria,/places/413163,An ancient city of Picenum that may have originated as colony established by Etruscans from Adria in the Veneto region.
Heba,/places/413164,A Roman colony that was established in the third or second century B.C., Heba lay near modern Magliano. Funerary evidence indicate previous Etruscan occupation at the site.
*Hercules Curinus,/places/413165,A sanctuary dedicated to Hercules Curinus located near Sulmo.
Helvia Ricina,/places/413166,An ancient settlement in Picenum at modern Villa Potenza in Marche, Comune di Macerata, Italy.
Helvillum,/places/413167,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D2 Helvillum
Helvinus? (river),/places/413168,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F2 Helvinus? fl.
Himella fl.,/places/413169,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Himella fl.
Hispellum,/places/413170,Hispellum (modern Spello) is an ancient settlement of Umbria that became a Roman colony in the first century BC.
Histonium,/places/413171,Histonium, on the Adriatic coast, was a chief town of the Frentani.
Horta,/places/413172,The Etruscan settlement of *Hurta (the modern Orte) was close to the Vadimonis Lacus where the Romans fought, and won, two engagements against Etruscan armies. 
Iguvium,/places/413174,An Umbrian hilltown, Iguvium is best known as the find-spot of the Iguvine Tables.
*Incerulae,/places/413175,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 *Incerulae
Interamna Nahars,/places/413178,An Umbrian center founded in the seventh century B.C. that became an important Roman municipality along the Via Flaminia. 
Interamnia Praetuttiorum,/places/413179,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Interamnia Praetuttiorum
Intercisa/Petra Pertusa,/places/413180,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Intercisa/Petra Pertusa
Interocrium,/places/413181,A Sabine town that was later known as a mansio on the course of the Via Salaria.
Interpromium,/places/413182,A village of the Marrucini, forming a station on the Via Claudia Valeria between Corfinium and Teate.
Lucus Feroniae,/places/413184,A sanctuary and grove of Feronia and an associated settlement located along the Via Tiberina in the territory of Capena.
Lugnano,/places/413185,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C3 Lugnano
Luni sul Mignone,/places/413186,Luni sul Mignone is a site with archaeological evidence for habitation in the final second millennium BC, continuing into the Italian Iron Age.
Magliano Sabina,/places/413188,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Magliano Sabina
Manliana,/places/413189,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Manliana
Marrucini,/places/413190,The Marrucini were an Italic tribe centered around Teate in the Abruzzo. In conflict with Rome through the end of the Second Samnite War, the Marrucini became allied with Rome thereafter. Their language was likely in the Sabellic family.
Marsi,/places/413191,The Marsi were an ancient Italic tribe. Their chief center was located at Marruvium.
Marsiliana d’Albegna,/places/413192,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A3 Marsiliana d’Albegna

Martanum,/places/413194,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 Martanum
Maternum,/places/413195,Maternum was a settlement of ancient Etruria that is known from the Peutinger Table. It is located along the Via Clodia between Saturnia and Tuscana.
Matilica,/places/413196,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Matilica
Matrinum,/places/413197,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 G3 Matrinum
Matrinus? fl.,/places/413198,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Matrinus? fl.
Metaurus (river),/places/413199,Metaurus fl. (Metauro river) flows from near Monte dei Frati in the Apennine Mountains to the Adriatic Sea. The Metaurus was the site of two key battles in antiquity. The first, in 207 BC, saw the defeat of Hasdrubal Barca by the consuls Marcus Livius Salinator and Gaius Claudius Nero. The second, the Battle of Fano, saw Aurelian defeat the Alamanni in AD 271.
Mevania,/places/413200,Mevania (modern Bevagna) was a Roman municipium in Umbria located on the Via Flaminia. The town was enrolled in the tribus Aemilia.
Mevaniola,/places/413201,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 Mevaniola

Misus (river),/places/413204,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E1 Misus fl.
Mola di Monte Gelato,/places/413205,An ancient settlement 30 km north of Rome that was excavated from 1986-90. An imperial villa existed on the site up until the third century AD.
Montariolo,/places/413206,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Montariolo

Monti della Tolfa,/places/413214,Monti della Tolfa, a volcanic group of mountains in the Anti-Apennines in the northern part of Lazio in central Italy.
Poggio Civitate (Murlo),/places/413216,An Etruscan elite complex of the seventh and sixth centuries BC located at Poggio Civitate, a hill adjacent to the medieval town of Murlo and about 25 km south of Siena.
Musarna,/places/413217,Musarna is an ancient Etruscan settlement discovered in 1849 just west of Viterbo, Italy. The École française de Rome has been conducting excavations at the site since 1983.
Naharcer,/places/413219,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Naharcer

Nemora Vacunae,/places/413223,Shrine dedicated to a rural divinity of the Sabina.
Nepet,/places/413224,Nepet had become a Roman town before 396 BC when Livy dubs it, along with Sutrium, as one of the "keys" to Etruria. It became a Roman colony in 383 BC and a municipium after the Social War.
Nequinum/Narnia,/places/413225,Nequinum/Narnia (modern Narni) was an ancient settlement in Umbria. It became a Latin colony in 299 BC.
Novilara,/places/413226,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Novilara
Nuceria,/places/413227,Nuceria (modern Nocera Umbra) is an ancient town in Umbria, perhaps founded in the seventh century B.C. by Camerinum.
Numana,/places/413228,Numana was a settlement of ancient Picenum located south of Ancona.
Nursia,/places/413229,Nursia was the northernmost city of the Sabines.
Ocriculum,/places/413231,An ancient Umbrian city that became allied with Rome in 308 B.C.
[Orcla],/places/413233,[Orcla] or Norchia is an ancient Etruscan settlement located near Tarquinia and along the line of the Roman Via Clodia. 
Ortona,/places/413234,An ancient site in Italy that most likely originates with the Frentani.
Osa fl.,/places/413235,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A3 Osa fl.
Ossaia,/places/413236,Site of a Late Republican and Imperial Roman villa (cited: BAtlas 42 C2 Ossaia)
Ostia Aterni,/places/413237,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 G4 Ostia Aterni
Ostra,/places/413238,Ostra was an ancient town of Umbria.
Paeligni,/places/413240,An ancient Oscan tribe of eastern Italy, the Paeligni are mentioned in the historical sources first in the fourth century BC when they oppose Rome during the Second Samnite War. The Paeligni came into alliance with Rome at the end of the fourth century BC but again took sides against Rome in the Social War.
Paganica,/places/413241,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Paganica
Pallanum,/places/413242,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 G4 Pallanum
Pallia (river),/places/413243,Pallia fl is a tributary of the Tiber.
Palmensis Ager,/places/413244,Pliny the Elder discusses the Palmensis Ager in connection with his description of the Praetutii.
Passo Corese,/places/413245,Passo Corese is located near Cures (Fara in Sabina). The site is often connected with Titus Tatius' march on Rome in 747 B.C.
Pausulae,/places/413246,Pausulae was a town of Picenum mentioned by Pliny the Elder. It was a Municipium of Regio V.
Peltuinum,/places/413247,Peltuinum was a settlement of the Vestini located along the Via Claudia Nova. The town is notable as the birthplace of the Roman general  Gnaeus Domitius Corbulo.
Perusia,/places/413248,A city of ancient Umbrian and Etruscan origin, Perusia aided Rome during the Second Punic War but was sieged and reduced by Octavian in the first century BC during campaigns against Lucius Antonius. It was rebuilt by Augustus and became Colonia Vibia Augusta Perusia quite late, in AD 251-3, under Trebonianus Gallus.
Pescara,/places/413249,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Pescara
Phalacrinae,/places/413251,A Roman town in which the emperor Vespasian was born in A.D. 9.
Piano Tondo,/places/413252,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Piano Tondo
Picenum,/places/413253,Picenum was a region of Central Italy, extending along the coast of the Adriatic Sea from the mouth of the Aesis to that of the Matrinus, and inland as far as the central Apennines.
Pieve Socana,/places/413254,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B1 Pieve Socana
Pinna,/places/413255,Pinna (modern Penne) was a center of the Vestini. The site came under Roman control after the Social War (89 BC).
Pisaurum,/places/413256,Pisaurum (modern Pésaro) was founded as a Roman colony in the territory of the Picentes in 184 BC.
Pisaurus (river),/places/413257,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Pisaurus fl.
Pitigliano,/places/413258,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Pitigliano
Pitino,/places/413259,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Pitino
Pitinum,/places/413260,An ancient center of the Vestini.
Pitinum Mergens,/places/413261,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Pitinum Mergens
Pitinum Pisaurense,/places/413262,An ancient settlement in Umbria, known mostly via its inclusion in the texts of Pliny the Elder and Ptolemy, as well as by means of various epigraphic evidence.
Planina,/places/413263,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Planina
Plestia,/places/413264,Plestia was a municipium of the tribus Ufentina.
Plestinus L.,/places/413265,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D2 Plestinus L.
Poggio Buco,/places/413266,Poggio Buco was a pre-Roman site located in the valley of the Fiora river. Its archaeological remains include those of a circuit wall and a necropolis. The archaeological site is located ca. 9 km west of Pitigliano.
Poggio Sommavilla,/places/413267,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Poggio Sommavilla

Potentia,/places/413272,A city settled in an area subjugated by Rome during the fourth century BC. The local populace rebelled against Rome after the defeat at Cannae (216 BC), however the defeat of the Carthaginians eventually led to Potentia's reincorporation into the Roman sphere.
Praetuttii,/places/413273,The Praetuttii were an ancient tribe of central Italy.
Prolaqueum,/places/413275,A statio on the road from Nuceria to Ancona.

Reate,/places/413283,Reate (modern Rieti) was a major Sabine center that came to be captured by Manius Curius Dentatus in late third century BC.
Regis Villa/Regae,/places/413284,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 Regis Villa/Regae
Respampani,/places/413285,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 Respampani
Rosia Campus,/places/413286,A plain in the territory of the Sabines near Reate, reputed to have the most fertile soils in Italy.
Rostrata Villa,/places/413287,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Rostrata Villa
Rusellae,/places/413288,An Etruscan city captured by Rome in 294 BC. Rusellae's >2 mile circuit of megalithic walls represent an important early instance of stone fortification walling in the Italian peninsula.
Sabatinus L.,/places/413290,A volcanic lake in Latium north of Rome.
Sabini,/places/413291,The Sabini (Sabines) were an Italic tribe of central Italy and belonged to the Osco-Umbrian language group. Their territory straddled parts of the modern regions of  Lazio, Umbria, and the Abruzzo. Ancient writers connect them with Rome at the time of its foundation, as represented by the episode of the 'rape of the Sabine women' reported by various ancient authors.
Sacraria,/places/413292,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Sacraria
Saena,/places/413293,Saena was an Etruscan city that received a Roman colony (Saena Iulia) in the time of Augustus.
Sagrus (river),/places/413294,A river of eastern Italy (modern Sangro).
S. Anatolia,/places/413295,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E4 S. Anatolia

Sarsina,/places/413306,Sarsina was a town of the Umbri that was captured by Cornelius Scipio in 271 B.C. and was the birthplace of the Latin author Plautus. The necropolis at Sarsina has been extensively studied. 
Sarteano,/places/413307,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Sarteano
Sena (river),/places/413309,The Nevola river.
Sena Gallica,/places/413310,Located at the mouth of the river Misa, Sena Gallica was founded by the Senonian Gauls in the fourth century BC and became the site of Rome's earliest Adriatic colony before 280 BC. Pompeius Magnus destroyed the city in 82 BC.
Senones,/places/413311,An ancient Gallic tribe that entered Italy after 400 BC and settled on the Adriatic coast from Forlì to Ancona, marking the so-called Ager Gallicus.
Sentinum,/places/413312,An ancient town in the region of Italy now known as Le Marche, Sentinum is perhaps best known for the pivotal Battle of Sentinum of the Third Samnite War that took place nearby in 295 BC.
Sepernates?,/places/413313,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Sepernates?
Septempeda,/places/413314,Septempeda was an ancient settlement of Picenum. Its Roman phase began as a conciliabulum in the third century BC.
Sestinum,/places/413315,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C1 Sestinum
Settefinestre,/places/413316, Late Republican Roman slave-run villa owned by the senatorial family of the Volusii; cited: BAtlas 42 A4 Settefinestre
Soracte M.,/places/413317,Soracte M. (Monte Soratte) is a mountain near Rome, Italy, the highest peak of which rises to 691 masl (2,267 ft). A site of ritual activity in antiquity, the mountain was sacred to Dis Pater.
Sorano,/places/413318,Sorano was a Villanovan and, later, Etruscan settlement.
Sorrina,/places/413319,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Sorrina
Spoletium,/places/413320,An ancient city along the route of the Via Flaminia; an initial colony was established there in 241 BC. 
Statonia,/places/413321,An ancient city of south Etruria.
Statulae,/places/413322,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Statulae
Suana,/places/413323,Suana (Sovana) has Etruscan origins but later became a Roman municipium. In the fifth century A.D. it became an episcopal see.
Suasa,/places/413324,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Suasa
Succosa,/places/413325,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A4 Succosa
Superaequum,/places/413326,One of three towns of the Paeligni which possessed municipal rights.
Sutrium,/places/413328,An ancient settlement along the line of what would become the Roman Via Cassia and described by Livy, together with Nepet, as one of the keys to Etruria. A Latin colony was founded at the site after the fall of Veii.
Tadinae,/places/413330,Tadinae (Sant'Antonio della Rasina to the west of Gualdo Tadino) is an ancient municipium of Umbria and was a road station on the Via Flaminia.
Talamone,/places/413331,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 A3 Talamone
Tarchna/Tarquinii,/places/413332,An ancient city of Etruria and the leading city of the doudecim populi Etruriae, Tarquinia (called Tarch(u)na or Tarchna in Etruscan) was a major urban center of ancient Italy.
Teate,/places/413333,Originally named Teate Marrucinorum, Teate (modern Chieti) was the principal settlement of the Marrucini. Strabo attributes its origins to Arcadian Greeks.
Tessuinus fl.,/places/413335,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Tessuinus fl.
Tetricus M.,/places/413336,Tetricus M.,  a mountain group in Italy, part of the central Apennines.

Tinea (river),/places/413340,The Topino river in Umbria.

Tiora Matiene,/places/413342,Tiora Matiene was the site of an ancient oracle of the god Mars.

Tolentinum,/places/413344,Tolentinum was a town of Picenum that is listed as having municipal status in the Liber Coloniarum.
Tolenus (river),/places/413345,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Tolenus fl.
Traianus?,/places/413346,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B4 Traianus?
Trasumennus L.,/places/413347,Trasumennus L. (Lake Trasimeno) is the largest lake of the Italian peninsula and the site of a major engagement of the Second Punic War on June 21, 217 BC.
Trea,/places/413348,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Trea
Trebiae,/places/413349,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Trebiae
Trebula Mutuesca,/places/413350,Trebula Mutuesca or Trebula Mutusca was one of two Sabina cities bearing the name Trebula.

Trevignano,/places/413352,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Trevignano
Truentus (river),/places/413353,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 E3 Truentus fl.
Tuder,/places/413354,Tuder, modern Todi, is an ancient city of Umbria. Its foundation likely occurred during the eighth/seventh centuries BC, although legendary traditions associate the site with the activities of Herakles. 
Tuficum,/places/413355,Tuficum was an ancient city of Umbria located on the Aesis river. It became a municipium of the tribus Oufentina.
Tuscana,/places/413356,An ancient city that traced its legendary origins to Ascanius, son of Aeneas. The site became an important Etruscan mercantile center and eventually achieved Roman municipal status in 88 BC.
Umbria,/places/413360,The eponymous region of the Umbri, an ancient Italic people who spoke the Umbrian language. The physical geography of the landlocked region is hilly and dominated by the Appennine Mountains.
*Umbro (river),/places/413362,The Ambra flows from the foot of Monte Luco to the Arno river.
Urbs Salvia,/places/413364,An ancient city of Regio V (Picenum) where a Roman colony was founded in the second century B.C.
Urvinum Hortense,/places/413365,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Urvinum Hortense
Urvinum Mataurense,/places/413366,Urvinum Mataurense (modern Urbino).
Vacchereccia,/places/413369,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Vacchereccia
Vadimonis L.,/places/413370,A partially dry lake of ancient Etruria near Orte. The Romans were victorious in two battles fought against the Etruscans there (310 and 283 BC).
Velini L.,/places/413371,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Velini L.
Velini L.,/places/413372,A lake formed by three rivers (Avens, Himella and Tolenus) in the territory of the Sabines.
Velzna/*Volsinii Veteres/Urbiventus,/places/413373,Volsinii Veteres was one of the most powerful and important cities of Etruria, as it was the location of the important federal sanctuary located at the Fanum Voltumnae.
Verucchio,/places/413374,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C1 Verucchio
Vespasiae,/places/413375,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Vespasiae
Vestini,/places/413376,The Vestini were an ancient tribe of Italy and lived in the southern part of the modern Abruzzo, between the Gran Sasso and the northern bank of the Aterno river. A major center was located at Pitinum.
Vettona,/places/413377,Vettona (modern Bettona) is an ancient settlement of Umbria located between Perusia and Mevania. Pliny the Elder lists it among the municipalities of Umbria, and it also numbered as one of the “xv Populi Umbriae".
Vicarello,/places/413379,A large, Roman imperial estate covering ca. 2,000 ha on the shores of Lake Bracciano. The name may derive from Vicus Aurelius, suggesting a connection with Marcus Aurelius.
Vicus Martis,/places/413380,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Vicus Martis
Vicus Matrini,/places/413381,Vicus Matrini was a mansio along the Via Cassia, located between Sutri and Forum Cassi. The site's name is attested on the Peutinger Table.

Vignanello,/places/413383,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Vignanello
Villa S. Silvestro,/places/413384,The remains of a Republican temple podium now support a Christian church at Villa S. Silvestro in Umbria. The temple's podium likely dates, in its first phase, to the third century B.C.
Villalfonsina,/places/413385,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 H4 Villalfonsina
Visentium,/places/413386,Visentium (Bisenzio) was an Etruscan settlement located on the shore of Lago di Bolsena. The site has yielded especially important evidence for Iron Age and Etruscan period burials.
Vittorito,/places/413387,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Vittorito
Volsiniensis L.,/places/413388,A volcanic lake of northern Latium formed by the collapse of the Vulsini volcano. Roman sources record volcanic activity at the site as late as the second century BC.
Volsinii,/places/413389,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Volsinii
Volusii,/places/413391,A villa associated with the Volusii Saturnini built ca. 50 BC.
Vomanus (river),/places/413392,The Vomano river in Abruzzo flows into the Adriatic Sea.
Vulci,/places/413393,Vulci (originally Velch or Velx in Etruscan) was an Etruscan city 80 km northwest of Rome. Vulci was one of the duodecim populi Etruriae.

Ad Duas Lauros,/places/422808,The toponym 'Ad Duas Lauros' refers to a large imperial property at the third mile of the Via Labicana and today comprised of the archaeological park of Centocelle. The site is mentioned in the Liber Pontificalis as that of a large imperial villa in which Helena, mother of Constantine I, lived. Archaeological work conducted in the late 1990s identified the remains of substantial Republican period villas in the same area, with evidence of both elite dwellings and viticulture. The villas identified are the Villa della Piscina and the Villa Ad Duas Lauros.
Ad Gallinas Albas,/places/422809,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B1 Ad Gallinas Albas

Ad Pictas,/places/422813,Ad Pictas is a road station east of Rome, known mostly for its role in Sulla's march on Rome in 88 B.C. The precise location of the statio continues to be debated.
Ad Quintanas,/places/422814,Ad Quintanas is the name of a road station on the Via Labicana.

Ad Turres,/places/422818,Ad Turres was located on the Via Aurelia some 10 miles from Lorium and 12 miles from Pyrgi.

Aeflanus M.,/places/422820,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Aeflanus M.
Aefula,/places/422821,Aefula was an ancient settlement of Latium that had disappeared by the time of Pliny the Elder, although the cult of Bona Dea there continued to flourish.
Aequi,/places/422822,The Aequi were an ancient Italic tribe of northeast Latium in the first millennium BC.
Afilae,/places/422823,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 E2 Afilae
Alba Longa?,/places/422824,Alba Longa, located in the Alban Hills southeast of Rome, was the chief city and founder of the Latin League. Conflict with Rome caused Alba's destruction in the seventh century B.C. The legendary history of Romulus and Remus connects them to the royal lineage of the city.
Albanus L.,/places/422825,A volcanic lake in ancient Latium at the foot of Albanus Mons, Albanus Lacus (Alban Lake) is connected with the site of the city of Alba Longa and, later, with imperial properties of the Flavian house.
Albanus M.,/places/422826,The second highest summit of the Alban Hills, Mons Albanus is an extinct volcano with an elevation of 950 m (3,117 ft). In the middle of the first millennium BC there may have been volcanic activity as noted by the historian Livy. The mountain was sacred for Latin peoples who held important festivals there and a major shrine to Iuppiter Latiaris stands on the mountain top.
Albuccione,/places/422827,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Albuccione
Albunea fl.,/places/422828,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 Albunea fl.
Algidus,/places/422829,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Algidus
Algidus M.,/places/422830,Algidus M. refers to the eastern rim of the dormant Alban volcano in the Alban Hills of central Italy.
Alsium,/places/422831,Alsium served as a port for Caere, together with Fregenae.
L’Altare,/places/422832,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C3 L’Altare
Anagnia,/places/422833,Anagnia was a Hernican town that sided with Rome against the Volscians and later became civitas sine suffragio.
Anio (river),/places/422834,The Anio river (modern Aniene) is a river of northern Latium.
Annunziatella,/places/422835,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Annunziatella
Antemnae,/places/422836,Antemnae is an ancient Latin settlement located north of Rome near the point where the Anio and Tiber rivers intersect.  Connected with Rome's early history, Antemnae was involved in episodes such as the 'Rape of the Sabine Women' and Romulus is said to have celebrated a triumph over the Antemnates in 752 BC.
Antium,/places/422837, Antium ranked as one of the most important and most powerful centers of Latium and was captured by Rome at the close of the Latin War in the fourth century B.C. Imperial Antium was well known for a number of coastal villas.
Antonini,/places/422838,The so-called 'Villa of the Antonines', located near Genzano di Roma in the Alban Hills.
Aquae Albulae,/places/422840,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Aquae Albulae
Aquae Albulae,/places/422841,A group of springs located west of Tibur (modern Tivoli). The main spring, known as Lago della Regina, preserves traces of an ancient Roman bath.
Arcinazzo,/places/422842,An imperial villa of the Trajanic and Hadrianic periods located on the Altipiani di Arcinazzo.
Ardea,/places/422843,Ardea was an ancient settlement of the Rutuli in Latium.

Campus Martius,/places/422863,The Campus Martius or "field of Mars" is the name given to the level ground between the slopes of the Capitoline, the Quirinal, and Pincian hills, and the Tiber river.

Cremera (river),/places/422912,The Cremera is a small stream in Lazio that played a role in the fourth century BC war between Rome and the Etruscan city-state of Veii.
Crepaddosso,/places/422913,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Crepaddosso
Crustumerium,/places/422914,An ancient town of Latium located at the headwaters of the Allia river, very close to the territory of the Sabines, Crustumerium figures in Rome's early history. The Romans conquered the site in 500 BC and formed the tribus Crustumina or Clustumina  in 471 BC.
Dea Dia, T.,/places/422916,The Arval Brethren cultivated the cult of the Dea Dia.
Diana, T.,/places/422917,A site sacred to Diana near Lake Nemi, comprised of a Tuscan-style sanctuary and a sacred grove. 
Ficana,/places/422921,An ancient city of Latium that was said to have been conquered by Ancus Marcius, Ficana was located near the eleventh mile of the Via Ostiensis. Excavation at the site has produced important evidence for the urban center beginning from the eighth century BC. Pliny the Elder mentions Ficana as one of the lost cities of Latium.
Ficulea,/places/422922,Ficulea was an ancient city of Latium situated between Rome and Nomentum.
Fidenae,/places/422923,Fidenae was an ancient city of Latium.

Fregenae,/places/422930,An ancient town of Etruria, Fregenae was located between Alsium and the mouth of the river Tiber.
Gabii,/places/422932,An ancient Latin city located on the line of the Republican Via Praenestina connecting Rome to Praeneste. Gabii is allied to Rome from an early date and flourished during the archaic period, declining by the time of Augustus.
Giordani,/places/422934,A fourth century AD catacomb at Rome.
La Giostra,/places/422935,A fortified site on the Via Appia dating to the Republican period.

Hernici,/places/422944,The Hernici (Hernicans) were an Italic tribe of first millennium B.C. Latium. Their territory was bounded by the Trerus fl. (Sacco) and the Lacus Fucinus (Fucine Lake).

Labicum,/places/422952,Originally a member of the Latin League, the city of Labicum was taken by the Romans ca. 418 B.C. By the time of Augustus, the site was almost certainly deserted and its precise location remains debated today.
