Lanuvium,/places/422956,Lanuvium was an important city of Latium located south of the Alban Hills. After opposing Rome at the battle of Aricia (504 B.C.) and Lake Regillus (496 B.C.), Lanuvium was captured by the Romans in 338 B.C.
Largo Preneste,/places/422957,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Largo Preneste
Latium Vetus,/places/422958,Latium Vetus is an historical region of Italy. Latium Vetus begins south of the Tiber river and extends as far as Circeo, at which point the boundary of Latium Adiectum is reached.
Laurentes,/places/422959,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B3 Laurentes
Lavinium,/places/422960,An ancient city of Latium on the Numicus river that was founded, according to Virgil, by Aeneas.
Lepinus M.,/places/422961,Lepinus M., a mountain range of central Italy that belongs to the Anti-Apennines.

Lorium,/places/422963,An ancient town on the Via Aurelia.

Monte del Grano,/places/422973,Monte del Grano is a popular name that was assigned to a mausoleum once thought to belong to Alexander Severus, although that assignation is no longer supported. The archaeological remains are now part of the Parco XVII Aprile 1944.

Monteverde,/places/422978,The hill of Monteverde, a part of the Ianiculum hill to the west of the Tiber river, was a source of a brown, lithoid tuff (tufo di Monteverde) that was quarried for use as a building material from the second century BC.
Montioni,/places/422979,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Montioni

Naumachia,/places/422983,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Naumachia
Nemorensis L.,/places/422984, Nemorensis Lacus or Lake Nemi is a small, volcanic lake in Latium located south of Rome. The lake is known for its adjacent sanctuary of the goddess Diana and for a number of sunken Roman ships of the first century AD that were recovered from it.
Nettuno,/places/422985,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C4 Nettuno
Nomentum,/places/422986,The Latin town of Nomentum and Rome were linked by means of the Via Nomentana. In Livy's history the town, a member of the Latin League, is captured by Lucius Tarquinius Priscus. Nomentum was one of a number of towns captured by Tarquinius. The Romans granted the town civitas sine suffragio after 338 B.C.
Norba,/places/422987,Norba, located in the Monti Lepini, was a member of the Latin League (ca. 499 B.C.) and became a Latin colony ca. 492 B.C. The city was destroyed in the early first century B.C.
Numicus,/places/422988,The Numicus flumen was a river of Latium connected with the legendary history of Aeneas. Modern Fosso di Pratica in Italy.
Octavii,/places/422991,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Octavii

Osteria dell’Osa,/places/422994,The site of a major Iron Age necropolis (Latial chronology) composed of over 600 burials.
Ostia,/places/422995,The port city of ancient Rome located at the mouth of the river Tiber.
Pedum?,/places/422997,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Pedum?
Pianabella,/places/422998,A large Christian basilica discovered in 1976 several hundred meters southeast of the Porta Laurentina of Ostia. The original phase dates to the end of the fourth century AD.

Pometia,/places/423005,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Pometia
Pompeo,/places/423006,A villa attributed to Cnaeus Pompeius.
Pons Mulvius,/places/423008,Pons Mulvius (the Milvian Bridge) is a Roman bridge over the Tiber river. The original phase of the bridge dates to the consulship of Gaius Claudius Nero in 206 BC. The bridge is most famous as the site of a decisive battle between Maxentius and Constantine I fought in AD 312.
Ponte di Tuscolo,/places/423009,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Ponte di Tuscolo
Ponte Mammolo,/places/423010,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Ponte Mammolo
Ponte Salario,/places/423011,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Ponte Salario
Portus,/places/423012,The great ancient maritime port of Rome, located on the right-hand bank of the Tiber river.
Praeneste,/places/423013,An ancient city of central Italy, the eighth and seventh century B.C. origins of which demonstrate high level trade contact with the Eastern Mediterranean world. The city withdrew from the Latin League (499 BC) and opposed Rome in the Latin war; Cincinnatus eventually subdued Praeneste. Sulla founded a new colony there in the first century B.C.
Prati Fiscali,/places/423014,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Prati Fiscali
Prima Porta,/places/423015,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B1 Prima Porta
Priscilla,/places/423016,A Christian catacomb within an ancient quarry on the Via Salaria that was in use from the second until the fourth centuries AD. The Catacomb of Priscilla was likely named for  Priscilla, a member of the gens Acilia, and contains the oldest known Marian painting (third century AD).
Quadraro,/places/423018,A Roman villa near the line of the Aqua Claudia located in the modern Via del Quadraro. The villa is dated to the first century B.C. or first century A.D. Following remodelling in the third century, the villa's occupation ends in the fourth century.
Quintilii,/places/423019,A suburban villa built by Sextus Quintilius Maximus and Sextus Quintilius Condianus (consuls in A.D. 151).
Quintilio Varo,/places/423020,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Quintilio Varo
Redicolo,/places/423022,The Tomb of Annia Regilla (vix. AD 125-160), the wife of Herodes Atticus. The tomb is also erroneously known as the "Temple of the God Rediculum" and was used in the Middle Ages as a hay barn.
Regillus? L.,/places/423023,An ancient lake that was the site of a Roman military victory in 496 BC; the precise location of the lake cannot be determined.
Robigo?, T.,/places/423024,The sanctuary of the god Robigus, located at the sixth mile of the Via Cassia. The Romans celebrated the festival of Robigalia on 25 April.
Roma,/places/423025,The capital of the Roman Republic and Empire.
La Rustica,/places/423026,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 La Rustica
Sabina,/places/423028,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Sabina
Sacer Mons,/places/423029,Sacer Mons is a hill on the banks of the Anio river and is connected, traditionally, with the episode of the secession of the Roman plebs of 494 BC.

S. Agnese,/places/423035,A titular church on the Via Nomentana, S. Agnese houses the remains of the eponymous saint. The present church was built by Pope Honorius I in the seventh century AD, on the site of a fourth century basilica built by Constantine I.

S. Antonio,/places/423037,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 S. Antonio
S. Callisto,/places/423038,A large catacomb on the Via Appia south of Rome notable especially for its so-called 'Crypt of the Popes'.  The catacomb covers approximately 15 hectares.

S. Laurentius,/places/423046,The Papal Basilica of Saint Lawrence outside the Walls (Basilica Papale di San Lorenzo fuori le Mura) is one of the Seven Pilgrim Churches of Rome. The basilica serves as the shrine and tomb dedicated to Saint Lawrence and its earliest phases likely belong to the fourth century AD.
S. Lidano,/places/423047,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D3 S. Lidano
SS. Marcellino e Pietro,/places/423048,The church of Saints Marcellinus and Peter is a Roman Catholic church in Rome on the Via Merulana. Pope Siricius built the original church in the fourth century AD, close to the catacombs of Marcellinus and Peter. The relics of the saints were deposited in the church in 1256.
S. Maria di Galeria,/places/423049,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 B1 S. Maria di Galeria
S. Martino,/places/423050,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 D2 S. Martino
S. Passera,/places/423051,S. Passera is a Christian church on the Tiber river in Rome, opposite the Basilica of Saint Paul Outside the Walls. The current church dates to the ninth century and incorporated the remains of a Roman tomb. The church is traditionally connected to a community of local miners.
S. Paulus,/places/423052,One of Rome's four major papal basilicae, S. Paulus was founded by Constantine I in the early fourth century AD and expanded by Valentinian I in the AD 370s.
S. Petrus,/places/423053,The Basilica of St. Peter in Vatican City; currently a Renaissance edifice standing on the site of Old St. Peter's Basilica, a church built by Constantine I between AD 319 and 333. The holy site is located on the Mons Vaticanus in connection with the purported site of the burial of the Christian Saint Peter. (cited: BAtlas 43 B2 S. Petrus)

Satricum,/places/423060,An ancient settlement on the right bank of the river Astura, Satricum has a mixed heritage of Latins and Volscians. In 499 B.C. Satricum was a member of the Latin League, but was under Volscian control in 488 B.C. The site is noted for its sanctuary of Mater Matuta.
Saxa Rubra,/places/423061,Saxa Rubra (modern Grottarossa) is the name of a road station on the Via Flaminia nine Roman miles from the center of ancient Rome. It was at Saxa Rubra that Constantine I defeated Maxentius in AD 312.

Valerio Messala Corvino,/places/423113,An ancient place, cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Valerio Messala Corvino
Valvisciolo,/places/423114,An Iron Age settlement and necropolis located in the Monti Lepini near the abbey of Valvisciolo, characterized by polygonal masonry terrace walls. While the ancient name of the site is unknown, various proposals have been raised, including Sulmo (Savignoni, Mengarelli) and Pometia (Ogilvie). The settlement corresponds to the Latial II B phase and occupation ends ca. the late sixth century BC.
Varia,/places/423115,Varia (modern Vicovaro) was a settlement of the Sabines.
Veii,/places/423116,An important city of South Etruria located north-northwest of Rome, Veii was eventually sacked by the Romans in 396 B.C. The ancient city covered some 180 ha.
Velitrae,/places/423117,Velitrae (modern Velletri) was an ancient Volscian settlement. In the Roman Republican period, Velitrae was attacked by Marcus Furius Camillus (379 B.C.) and again by Cincinnatus (377 B.C.); the Romans controlled the site by 365 BC. The gens Octavia hailed from the city and a youthful Octavian spent time there.
Agora of Athens,/places/807514119,The marketplace of the ancient city of Athens in Greece.

Stoa of Zeus (Eleutherios),/places/649966334,The Stoa of Zeus Eleutherios was built on the west side of the Agora of Athens between 430-425 BC, in honor of Zeus "of Freedom"; the stoa, Doric in its external order, housed the shields of Athenians who had died fighting for the city.
Theater of Dionysus Eleuthereus,/places/649966335,Theatre on the south slope of the Acropolis in Athens.

Altar of Hieron II,/places/219478548,A monumental altar built around the third century B.C. that was probably dedicated to Zeus Eleutherios. Remains of the altar are located in the archaeological area of Neapolis in Syracuse, Sicily.

Santa Sofia,/places/59677979,A Longobard church in Benevento, Italy, listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2011.
Tchogha Zanbil,/places/459393126,An ancient Elamite complex founded ca. 1250 BC by the king Untash-Napirisha.
House of Meleager,/places/979775194,The so-called "House of Meleager" (VI.9.2) is a domus in Pompeii of the "Samnite" type that was excavated first in 1829, then again in 1836 and 1966. The interior boasts rich painted decoration corresponding to Mau's first, third, and fourth styles.
Thodasa,/places/730120528,An unlocated community which was close to, and eventually entered into sympolitiea with, Kildara. 
Ionian League,/places/735295266,An Ancient Greek confederation originally formed in the sixth century BCE by twelve Ionian cities, with religious festivals celebrated at Panionia.

Minius (river),/places/236544,Minius fl. (modern Minho River) is a river of Galicia in the Iberian peninsula. Its ancient name likely derives from minius, the Latin term for cinnabar, and thus its name is, essentially, 'red river'.

La Graufesenque,/places/246410,La Graufesenque is the name of an archaeological site located in southern France at the point of the confluence of the Tarn and Dourbie rivers. Known in antiquity at Condatomagus, the site was famous for its large-scale production of high quality red terra sigillata pottery. This was produced in enormous quantities and exported across the western Roman world. Production of this type began in the reign of Augustus.

Wall of Media,/places/896945,The Wall of Media, also known as Mēdías teîchos or the Wall of Semiramis, at Habl as-Sahr is mentioned by Xenophon in the Anabasis as a defensive ditch at the Euphrates built on the orders of Artaxerxes in the fifth century BC.

Vangiones,/places/109410,The Vangiones were a Germanic tribe. They allied themselves with Ariovistus (58 BC) as he invaded Gaul and was defeated by Julius Caesar near Belfort. Drusus established two forts among the Vangiones, castrum Mogontiacum (13 BC, later Mainz) and another (14 BC) at Worms.

Tower of Seneca,/places/276094797,The Tower of Seneca is a sixteenth century castle in Corsica built atop the remains of a Roman watchtower.
Roman Forum at Syracuse,/places/649857186,The area, roughly situated between the island of Ortygia and the district of Acradina, was used as an agora and, in later years, as the forum of the city of Syracuse. It is now a public park where ancient ruins are still visible.
So-called Roman Gymnasium at Syracuse,/places/649857187,A monumental complex in the ancient city of Syracuse, probably built around the first century AD. It was initially identified as a gymnasium or a thermal bath; it includes the ruins of a theatre, a quadriporticus, and a temple.

Temple of Amphiaraus,/places/71107898,The Temple of Amphiaraus is an oracular temple dedicated to the hero/god Amphiaraus, located within the sanctuary of the Amphiareion. The site was believed to have healing powers and was particularly important in the Late Classical and Hellenistic periods (fifth to third centuries BCE).
Bryn Celli Ddu,/places/735015378,A Neolithic mound site on the island of Anglesey.
Via Claudia Augusta,/places/688514720,The Via Claudia Augusta was a Roman road that traversed the Alps, connecting the Po river valley to Rhaetia. It was begun by Claudius in AD 46/7.

Stabian Baths,/places/809159706,The Stabian Baths (VII, 1, 8) and  (VII,2) are located at the intersection of the Via Stabiana and the Via dell'Abbondanza. They are the oldest baths in Pompeii.

Santa Venera al Pozzo,/places/657287138,An archaeological area in Sicily, near Acireale, possibly related to the ancient settlement of Acium.
Kaymakçı,/places/886756147,A large Bronze Age settlement on the western shore of lake Marmara in western Anatolia, overlooking the central Gediz river valley.  The site is composed of an 8 hectare fortified citadel situated on a ridge, with evidence for a larger lower town below on the surrounding plain.
Enkomi,/places/13818291,Enkomi is the site of an important Middle Bronze Age settlement in eastern Cyprus.
Greta Bridge,/places/496316189,A Roman fort and associated vicus at modern Greta Bridge (UK).

Great Orme,/places/826210678,The Great Orme is a prominent limestone headland located in Llandudno on the north coast of Wales.
Grimes Graves,/places/567638603,Grimes Graves is the site of a Neolithic flint mining complex near Brandon in England that was in use from ca. 3000 to 1900 BC.
Cheddar Gorge,/places/535275913,The Cheddar Gorge is a limestone gorge in the Mendip Hills, near Somerset, England. The gorge and its many caves are the site of human activity dating back to the Upper Paleolithic.
Ruborough Camp,/places/145602471,Ruborough Camp is a triangular-shaped promontory fort, comprised of double bank with a medial ditch.
Cadbury Castle,/places/859366031,Cadbury Castle is a hill fort located in South Cadbury, Somerset, England.

Lake Matese,/places/689737510,Lake Matese is a glacial lake located in the Matese mountains at the foot of Monte Miletto and Monte Gallinola.
Bathampton Down,/places/689737511,Bathampton Down is a limestone plateau near Bath, England, with evidence for human settlement dating from the Mesolithic Period.
Bindon Hill,/places/689737512,Bindon Hill is the site of extensive Iron Age earthworks on a coastal hill area in Dorset, England.
Uffington White Horse,/places/858265770,The Uffington White Horse is stylized prehistoric hill figure dating to the later prehistoric period in England.
White Castle hillfort,/places/416269079,White Castle hillfort is an Iron Age fort located in Scotland.
Broch of Mousa,/places/6525101,The Broch of Mousa is a drystone broch in Scotland, dating ca. 400-200 BC.
Black Ball Camp,/places/721382239,Black Ball Camp or Gallox hill fort is an Iron Age hill fort in Dunster, Somerset, England.
Grabbist hill-fort,/places/721382240,Grabbist hill fort is an Iron Age hill-fort located west of Dunster in Somerset, England.
Worlebury Camp,/places/893850615,Worlebury Camp is the site of an Iron Age hill fort in Somerset, England.
Amphitheater of Alba Fucens,/places/535296216,A first century A.D. amphitheater at Alba Fucens built during the reign of Tiberius.
Santalla de Bóveda,/places/743134062,The Roman sanctuary of Santalla de Bóveda dates to the second through fourth centuries A.D. It is located in the parish of Santalla de Bóveda de Meralocated near Lugo. Discovered in 1926, the site is a protected national monument.
